Ideal Student Life Survey Student Responses Data for the Survey about Ideal Student Life and Key Factors

Youssef Khezami Khalil Boughzou Mouna Hmani

Link for Video presentation: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1AmzYizEc0DCb9hw8j69JAGY0JiGicicr

Background:
Engagement surveys define student engagement as involvement in activities and conditions that are linked with the level of satisfaction of student in their lives. A key assumption is that a perfect studet life is influenced by how an individual participates in activities and events.

Section 1: What is the global context of the data?
Understanding the psychology of students and understand their level of engagement and involvement in activities have a relation with their level of stress and satisfaction with their student life. This dataset consists of Student Responses to the survey about Ideal Student Life and key factors that are important in student life. Who has collected the data? The data was collected by Shivam Bansal a Data Scientist at H2O.ai Singapore. When has the data been collected? This Data has been posted on Kaggle in 2019 no further information was found. What are the features (Statistical variables) of the data? The first set of data can be divided into 4 parts: Descriptive statistics are used to describe the participants in a study (From 1 to 9) Questions about the engagement of students are explained with further details in the second section. (from Q1 to Q5) Rating for the level of engagement, stress, and Satisfaction ( Q6, Q7 and Q8) Free-format question to ask about the ideal student life. (Q9) The second set of data is going through more details from Q1 to Q5.

What are the instances (individuals) in the data? This sample of the data is taken from the National University of Singapore.

Section 2: The dataset can be used to answer key questions such as : -1)What factors lead to Stress, More Participation, More Interaction, More Satisfaction? -2)What factors lead to increased stress among the students? -3)What are the most important attributes for an Ideal Student Life?

Q1 -Visualization of how many people volunteered,participated in,interested in,passionate about and stressed about¶

we are interested in  knowing what activities are mostly done, participated in, interested in, passionate about and stressed about what factors
In [38]:
for col in dataframe.columns:
    subdf = dataframe[col][dataframe[col] == "Yes"]

    numqs, question = col.split("-", 1)
    question = question.replace(subs[numqs], "")
    if numqs not in plotdict:
        plotdict[numqs] = {}
    plotdict[numqs][question] = len(subdf)
In [39]:
for numqs, question in plotdict.items():
    df = pd.DataFrame({numqs:question.keys(), 'Yes':question.values()})
    ax = df.plot.bar(x=numqs, y='Yes', rot=90)

Interpretations:
-Plot 1(Acivities) : Children/Youth is the most 'sub activity" done by students and Arts/Cluture/Heritage are the least.
-Plot 2(Volunteering):Students volunteer in Societies and Interest Groups the most and Q2 halls, JRCS and/or Residential College CSCs.
-Plot3(Interests): Students are mostly interested in arts and culture and volunteering and least interested in 
other competitions.
-Plot4(Passion): Over 1000 students are passionate about animal weflare,Art/cluture/heritage,Children/Youth, health and well-being, Education. 
-Plot5 (stress): More than 2600 which constitute 95,2% of the students have academic issues causing stress.

### Q3 Text Mining using the most used words
In [43]:
criterions = ['stress', 'activities', 'academic', 'balanced', 'friendships']
keywords = {
    'stress': ['stress', 'personal'],
    'activites': ['activit', 'cca', 'social', 'work'],
    'academic': ['academ', 'stud', 'grad', 'learn'],
    'balanced': ['balanc'],
    'friendships': ['friend', 'fun', 'make']
}
varList = []

Interpretation: We divided the ideal student life into 5 attributes/categoties: Stundents are interested in doing activites +/ making friendship +/ their academic knowledge +/ a stress-free life or a balanced student life.
-Based on the WordCloud we got the most used words , classified and added them into lists for every attribites.
In [44]:
for answer in surveymain['Q9-What is an ideal student life ?']:
    verdict = []
    
    for criterion, texts in keywords.items():
        critfound = False
        for text in texts:

            
            if text in str(answer).lower():
                
                verdict.append(1)
                critfound = True
                break
        if critfound == False:
            verdict.append(0)
        varList.append(verdict)
    

Interpretation: Each student will have a correspondant vector [activities;volunteering;interests;passion;stress]
    with 5 binary variables: For eg: if he is only interested in stress and the feedback says something like
    'I want a stress free life',his vector would be [0;0;0;0;1],
    if he''s interested in volunteering , doing activities and a stressfree life, his vector would be [1;1;0;0;1].

     .

In [49]:
col_names = ['Q1-How many events have you Volunteered in ?', 'Q2-How many events have you Participated in ?', 'Q3-How many activities are you Interested in ?', 'Q4-How many activities are you Passionate about ?', 'Q5-What are your levels of stress ?', 'Q6-How Satisfied You are with your Student Life ?', 'Q7-How much effort do you make to interact with others ?', 'Q8-About How events are you aware about ?']
X = surveymain[col_names]
Y = surveymain['Gender']


X_train,X_test,Y_train,Y_test=train_test_split(X,Y,test_size=0.25,random_state=0)

logreg = LogisticRegression()


# fit the model with data
logreg.fit(X_train,Y_train)
Y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)


print("Accuracy:",metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred))
y_pred=logreg.predict(X_test)
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)
cnf_matrix
class_names=["Male","Female"] # name  of classes
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(class_names))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, class_names)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, class_names)
# create heatmap
sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(cnf_matrix), annot=True, cmap="YlGnBu" ,fmt='g')
ax.xaxis.set_label_position("top")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.title('Confusion matrix', y=1.1)
plt.ylabel('Actual label')
plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Accuracy: 0.5777777777777777
Out[49]:
Text(0.5, 257.44, 'Predicted label')

Through the logistic regression, we tried to predict the gender using the other variables. The accuracy of the model is estimated at 59,16% which is not a strong accuracy. This might be justified by the fact that other factor are not a strong determinant of gender, indeed the correlation between the gender and all the other activities is weak if not negligeable (this can be seen in the correlation matrix above).

Section 5:

Throughout this analysis we aimed the factors that cause an ideal Student life . Using a public set of surveys extracted from studetns from National University from Singapore, we aim at visualize the importance of each sub factor in relation with the main factor as well as factors between them. We started our analysis by cleaning our data, by removing unnecessary words and symbols, replacing column names, stemming, vectorization and text mining. Then to get informed about the Data content, we used word clouds and a Bar charts for Data visualization. We then proceeded to use 2 classification models:Random Forest and Logistic Regression. Each model was trained, tested, and evaluated by calculating the accuracy of its predictions. Finally, comparing all of our models we've come to undertand that the accuraccy of our models are not strong . This might be justified by the fact that gender is not a strong determinant of different other factors, indeed the correlation between the gender and all the other activities is weak if not negligeable (this can be seen in the correlation matrix above).
